The points P are called "control points" for the Bézier curve. The <a href="polygon">polygon</a> formed by connecting the Bézier points with <a href="line%20%28mathematics%29">lines</a>, starting with P and finishing with P, is called the "Bézier polygon" (or "control polygon"). The <a href="convex%20hull">convex hull</a> of the Bézier polygon contains the Bézier curve.

Sometimes it is desirable to express the Bézier curve as a <a href="polynomial">polynomial</a> instead of a sum of less straightforward <a href="Bernstein%20polynomial">Bernstein polynomial</a>s. Application of the <a href="binomial%20theorem">binomial theorem</a> to the definition of the curve followed by some rearrangement will yield:

