As an algebra, a unital commutative Banach algebra is <a href="semisimple%20algebra">semisimple</a> (i.e., its <a href="Jacobson%20radical">Jacobson radical</a> is zero) if and only if its Gelfand representation has trivial kernel. An important example of such an algebra is a commutative C*-algebra. In fact, when "A" is a commutative unital C*-algebra, the Gelfand representation is then an isometric *-isomorphism between "A" and "C"(Δ("A")) .




